{{Nihongo|'''''Extermination of Evil'''''|辟邪絵|Hekija-E}} is a set of five paintings depicting [[List of Asian mythologies|traditional Asian deities]] banishing evil. The paintings are collectively listed as a [[List of National Treasures of Japan (paintings)|National Treasure of Japan]] and held at the [[Nara National Museum]].

==Overview==
The paintings are thought to have been created during the 12th century, during the reign of [[Emperor Go-Shirakawa]] in the [[Heian period]];{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} they may have also been produced during the Kamakura period.{{sfn|Bunka.nii.ac.jp, 紙本著色辟邪絵}} The [[Japanese calligraphy|calligrapher]] is thought to be the same on the five scrolls as on the [[Hell Scroll (Tokyo National Museum)|Hell Scroll]] and the Demon of Punishment,{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} which were produced at roughly the same time.{{sfn|Bunka.nii.ac.jp, 紙本著色辟邪絵}} They are thought to have originally been a single handscroll,{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}}{{sfn|Bunka.nii.ac.jp, 紙本著色辟邪絵}} known as the "second edition of the Masuda family Hell Scroll", that was stored in the Rengeō-in Temple (now [[Sanjūsangen-dō]]). The paintings depict five benevolent deities in combat against evil, as represented by demons; the deities come from several cultures, including contemporary [[Japanese culture|Japanese]], [[Chinese culture|Chinese]], and [[Indian culture|Indian]]. They are thought to be associated with the Hell Transformation Screens then used in [[Nara Prefecture|Nara]] for repentance ceremonies at the end of each year, where the devout recited the names of the buddhas at [[Heijō Palace]].{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}}

The paintings were designated National Treasures of Japan on 6 June 1985,{{sfn|Bunka.nii.ac.jp, 紙本著色辟邪絵}} with the [[Accession number (library science)|accession number]] 1106.{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} They are located at the [[Nara National Museum]] in [[Nara, Nara|Nara]], [[Nara Prefecture]].{{sfn|Nara, Extermination of Evil}}

==Works==

===Tenkeisei===
[[File:Extermination of Evil Tenkeisei.jpg|300px|left|thumb|Tenkeisei]]
Tenkeisei (天刑星, literally meaning "the star [that metes out] heavenly punishment"), or the God of Heavenly Punishment, is a deity from the Chinese tradition of [[yin and yang]]. Originally a demon, he later took on a role in [[Vajrayana]] prayers. In the painting he is depicted fighting and consuming [[Ox-Head and Horse-Face|Gozu Tennô]], an ox-headed deity worshipped at the [[Yasaka Shrine|Gion Shrine]] (present day Yasaka) in [[Kyoto]].{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} The painting measures {{convert|26|by|39.2|cm|in}} and has the accession number 1106-1.{{sfn|Nara, Tenkeisei, God}}
{{clear}}

===Sendan Kendatsuba (Candana Gandharva)===
[[File:Extermination of Evil Sendan Kendatsuba.jpg|300px|thumb|left|Sendan Kendatsuba (Candana Gandharva)]]
Sendan Kendatsuba (栴檀乾闥婆, [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]] name Candana Gandharva) is one of the eight guardians of Buddhist law and one of the 33 manifestations of [[Avalokiteśvara]]. He is derived from an Indian [[Tutelary deity|patron god]] of music and believed to protect young people from the fifteen malevolent deities. He is drawn similar to in the ''Dôji mandara''.{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} The painting measures {{convert|25.8|by|77.2|cm|in}} and has the accession number 1106-2.{{sfn|Nara, Sendan Kendatsuba}}
{{clear}}

===Shinchū===
[[File:Extermination of Evil Shinchū.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Shinchū]]
The Divine Insect (神虫, Shinchū) is a deity depicted as a [[Bombyx mori|silkworm moth]]. It was known for miracles.{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} The painting measures {{convert|25.8|by|70|cm|in}} and has the accession number 1106-3.{{sfn|Nara, Shinchū, The Divine}}
{{clear}}

===Shōki===
[[File:Extermination of Evil Shōki.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Shōki]]
[[Zhong Kui|Shōki]] (鍾馗) is a deity told in Buddhist ''[[setsuwa]]'' (oral tales) to have protected [[Emperor Xuanzong of Tang]]. In the painting, Shōki is portrayed with a thick beard and large eyes. Wearing a black hat, robe, and tall boots, it is depicted as stabbing a demon.{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} The painting measures {{convert|25.8|by|45.2|cm|in}} and has the accession number 1106-4.{{sfn|Nara, Shōki, The Demon}}
{{clear}}

===Bishamon Ten===
[[File:Extermination of Evil Vaisravana.jpg|300px|thumb|left|[[Vaiśravaṇa|Bishamonten]]]]
Bishamonten (毘沙門天) is the Japanese name for [[Vaiśravaṇa]], the chief of the [[Four Heavenly Kings]]. In the image, he is depicted protecting followers of the [[Lotus Sutra]] from evil while carrying a bow. His equipment is similar to that found in Chinese paintings from the [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] and [[Song Dynasty|Song]] dynasties.{{sfn|e-Museum, Extermination of Evil}} The painting measures {{convert|25.8|by|76.5|cm|in}} and has the accession number 1106-5.{{sfn|Nara, Bishamon Ten}} 
{{clear}}

