{{Refimprove|date=October 2015}} {{Third-party|date=October 2015}} The '''Medieval Academy of America''', '''MAA''' (spelled '''Mediaeval''' until c. 1980)<ref>{{cite web |title=By-Laws |url=https://www.medievalacademy.org/page/ByLaws |publisher=The Medieval Academy of America |accessdate=2009-12-07 |quote=1. The name by which the Corporation shall be known is The Mediaeval Academy of America doing business as The Medieval Academy of America.}}</ref> is the largest organization in the United States promoting excellence in the field of [[medieval]] studies. It was founded in 1925 and is based in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. The academy publishes the quarterly journal ''[[Speculum (journal)|Speculum]]'', and awards prizes, grants, and fellowships such as the [[Haskins Medal]], which is named for [[Charles Homer Haskins]], one of the Academy's founders and its second president.<ref>[http://www.acls.org/programs/Default.aspx?id=390 Charles Homer Haskins] at website of the [[American Council of Learned Societies]]. Accessed 15 December 2016</ref>
The Academy supports research, publication and teaching in medieval art, archaeology, history, law, literature, music, philosophy, religion, science, social and economic institutions, and all other aspects of the Middle Ages.
{{As of|2017}}, the Academy's president was [[John Van Engen]];<ref>{{cite web |title=Officers |url=https://www.medievalacademy.org/page/Officers |publisher=The Medieval Academy of America |accessdate=2018-08-13}}</ref> the executive director is [[Lisa Fagin Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Lisa Fagin|title=About Lisa Fagin Davis|url=https://manuscriptroadtrip.wordpress.com/about/|website=Manuscript Road Trip|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>
